title: San Francisco Complaints/Settlements Related to 2020 Protests

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: San Francisco Complaints/Settlements Related to 2020 Protests
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Copies of lawsuits that details police misconduct brought against the city's police officers and/or the department by civilians or protesters who were injured during the 2020 George Floyd Protests from May 2020 to December 2021.

Copies of settlements that details the amount that plaintiffs who were injured by police during the 2020 George Floyd Protests received.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brianna Knibbs

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: San Francisco Complaints/Settlements Related to 2020 Protests
communications.communication:
Dear Requester,

Apologies for the delay. I am responding on behalf of the City Attorney’s Office to your below records request. The disclosable responsive records have been sent to you via FTP. Please see instructions below. Please note that we have withheld communications covered by attorney-client privilege (Cal. Gov’t Code §§ 7927.705, 7930.110; Cal. Evid. Code § 954) and attorney work product (Cal. Gov’t Code §§ 7927.705, 7930.110; Cal. Code of Civil Pro. § 2018.030), as well as responsive records that were filed under seal and covered under Penal Code sections 832.5, 832.7, and 832.8 and Evidence Code section 1040.

FTP Instructions:
You will be receiving an email from CCSF SFTP NO-Reply (no-reply@sfgov.org<mailto:no-reply@sfgov.org>) with a link to the responsive records. For best results, use Microsoft Edge internet browser. Please check your junk mail folder if you do not see the email in your inbox. Below are download instructions:



Guest Folder Files Download:

1.         Open the CCSF SFTP No-Reply email, click on View folder button.

2.         SFSecureShare will prompt to Register a new account or Guest Login if you have an existing account.

3.         After logging in, check box next to the folder files.

4.         Select Download button to download the files.



*The shared folder will expire on 12am 01/28/2024.

Please send replies to cityattorney@sfcityatty.org<mailto:cityattorney@sfcityatty.org>.


Sincerely,

[signature_540561676]Odaya Buta-Scott (she/her/hers)
Office of City Attorney David Chiu
odaya.buta@sfcityatty.org<mailto:odaya.buta@sfcityatty.org>, www.sfcityattorney.org<http://www.sfcityattorney.org/>
Find us on: Facebook<https://www.facebook.com/sfcityattorney/> Twitter<https://twitter.com/SFCityAttorney> Instagram<https://www.instagram.com/sfcityattorney/>

This message and any attachments are solely for the intended recipient and may include privileged or confidential information. If you have received this communication in error, please notify me immediately, and permanently delete this message and any attachments. Thank you.

title: Pickleball (Parks and Recreation Commission)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Pickleball (Parks and Recreation Commission)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all written or electronic communications, including attachments, between your department and members of USA Pickleball, (@usapickleball.org). This request seeks documents created between January 1, 2020 and the date this request is processed.

- Any emailed or formal complaints containing the word "pickleball." Please search between January 1 and the time this request is processed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jason Koebler

I have been working on your request and just wanted to ask for some clarification regarding the second part of your request where you state:

“Any emailed or formal complaints containing the word "pickleball." Please search between January 1 and the time this request is processed.”

I want to make sure if you are asking for just records from January 1, 2023 till the date your request came in (July 25th, 2023) , or if you are seeking from January 1st, 2020 as stated in the 1st part of your request?

title: Paul Howard Johnstone

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Paul Howard Johnstone
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to or mentioning Paul Howard Johnstone, who the FBI have already disclosed having records on (see attached document). I request that a cross-reference search be conducted with Daniel Ellsberg, Pentagon Papers, and Vietnam Task Force Study.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best

communications.communication:
Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@ic.fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 134 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 523 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,335 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 1,875 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
Record/Information Dissemination Section (RIDS) FBI-Information Management Division
170 Marcel Drive, Winchester, VA 22602-4843
Direct: (540) 868-4593
Fax: (540) 868-4391
Questions E-mail: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

title: Private Law Firms and Third Party Vendors (Federal Bureau of Investigation)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Private Law Firms and Third Party Vendors (Federal Bureau of Investigation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records relating or referring to the specific role of the “Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility” located within Washington, D.C. office of the private law firm Perkins Coie, or any private law firms or third party vendors in monitoring, surveillance, observation, questioning, interrogation, investigation, infiltration, and/or collection of information regarding any American individuals or groups, including any records relating or referring to how records about American individuals or groups have been, will be, or might be used.

All records relating to any coordination by, between or among the FBI, and the Washington, D.C. office, or any U.S. office of the private law firm Perkins Coie, Georgetown University’s Institute for Constitutional Advocacy and Protection (ICAP), or any private law firms or third party vendors, including any orders agreements, or instructions relating in any way to Joint Terrorism Task Force activities that include the monitoring, surveillance, questioning, interrogation, and/or investigation of individuals or organizations on the basis of organizational membership, political views or affiliation, or participation in protest activities related to January 6, 2021, or other protest activities or demonstrations.

All records relating to any coordination by, between or among the FBI and the Washington, D.C. office, or any U.S. office of the private law firm Perkins Coie, Georgetown University’s Institute for Constitutional Advocacy and Protection (ICAP), or any private law firms or third party vendors, including any orders agreements, or instructions relating in any way to Joint Terrorism Task Force activities that include the monitoring, surveillance, questioning, interrogation, and/or investigation of individuals or organizations in preparation for demonstrations that would occur at the United States Capitol on January 6, 2021, that include the names of organizations or individuals involved in protesting the results of the 2020 presidential election, or other related activities, demonstrations or protest activity.

All records relating to the monitoring, surveillance, observation, questioning, interrogation, investigation, infiltration and/or collection of information about American individuals or groups in connection with meetings or assemblies at or near the United States Capitol, in the months leading up to, during, and after January 6, 2021, within the “Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility” of the private law firm Perkins Coie Washington, D.C. office, Georgetown University’s Institute for Constitutional Advocacy and Protection (ICAP), or any private law firms or third party vendors.

All records relating to any database within the “Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility” of the private law firm Perkins Coie Washington, D.C. office, Georgetown University’s Institute for Constitutional Advocacy and Protection (ICAP), or any private law firms or third party vendors, used for law enforcement or domestic surveillance or monitoring purposes, or for maintaining information that includes the names of organizations or individuals involved in protesting or speaking out against the results of the 2020 presidential election, demonstrations or other related protest activities. 

The term “records” includes all records on communication preserved in any form, including: correspondence, documents, data, e-mails (including all attachments and history), text messages, web searches (including search histories), audio/visual tapes, faxes, files, guidance, analyses, notes, procedures, rules, manuals, and technical information.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Haley McLean

title: Chinese Communist Contacts with Scientists in the United States

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chinese Communist Contacts with Scientists in the United States
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records captioned "Chinese Communist Contacts with Scientists in the United States", a program described in a 1975 memo as "Development of selected scientists of ethnic Chinese background as foreign counterintelligence assets to be targeted against People's Republic of China (PRC) personnel and establishments in the U.S. and Canada" (https://www.archives.gov/files/research/jfk/releases/2018/docid-32989624.pdf). This program was previously disclosed to Mara Hvistendahl via FOIA in 2018 (https://theintercept.com/2020/02/02/fbi-chinese-scientists-surveillance/).

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies at FBI Headquarters. Please also conduct a search for records at the Alexandria Records Center. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

title: Sheriff's Use of Force/Complaints Data (Tehama County Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Sheriff's Use of Force/Complaints Data (Tehama County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. The total number of sheriff's deputy use of force incidents, broken down by type of force used, between 2013-2018 (separated by year).
2. The total number of people that deputies used force against, between 2013-2018 (separated by year).
3. The total number of use of force complaints reported between 2013-2018 (separated by year).
4. The total number of use of force complaints sustained between 2013-2018 (separated by year).
5. The policy manual of the sheriff's department.
6. The current union contract between the city and any sheriff's deputy/police officer unions.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Samuel Sinyangwe

communications.subject: PRA Response
communications.communication:
Dear Requester,

In the last month the responsibilities of responding to PRAs for the Sheriff's Office has unexpectedly changed and the County is no longer using the services provided for by Prentice Long, PC to respond to Public Records Request for the Tehama County Sheriff's Office.

Upon review of the records to your request it appears that this request has been responded to.  If you find this determination has been reached in error or are unsatisfied with the response you received, please notify us immediately. If we do not hear from you by December 12, we will proceed under the assumption that you are satisfied with the response you have received and will close the file on this request.  Please feel free to use the contact information below.  Thank you for seeking assistance with your Public Records Request through the Tehama County Counsel's Office. We hope that we may be of service to you in the future.

Thank you,


Daniel B. Klausner
Senior Deputy County Counsel
County of Tehama
727 Oak Street, Suite 223
Red Bluff, CA 96080
Phone (530) 527-9252
Fax (530) 527-9255
dklausner@co.tehama.ca.us<mailto:dklausner@co.tehama.ca.us>

title: CVL23167 and CVL013742

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: CVL23167 and CVL013742
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. On 2023-02-15 around 16:42, CVPD responded to a call for service categorized as a Suspicious Person	near 400 Oaklawn Ave. The incident number is 230215L00013742 or CVL013742.  I am looking for any call detail log, incident report ( including a narrative summary), investigatory report, arrest report, 911 audio recording, or log of drone activity for this event.

2. On 2023-03-18 around 09:38:00, CVPD responded to a call for service categorized as Domestic Violence	OR a Disturbance - General near 400 Oaklawn Ave. The incident number is 230318L00023167 or CVL23167.  I am looking for any call detail log, incident report ( including a narrative summary), investigatory report, arrest report, 911 audio recording, or log of drone activity for this event.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dhruv Mehrotra

title: Missouri "Don’t Tread on Me" license plates

communications.subject: The Missouri Sunshine Law Request: Missouri "Don’t Tread on Me" license plates
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the The Missouri Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Records that contain information on how many specialty "Don't Tread On Me" motor vehicle license plates (Statute Number 301.3163) were sold since their introduction broken down by year or month and year if possible.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Miller

title: Clearview AI contracts and policies

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Clearview AI contracts and policies
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Materials describing this agency's relationship with and use of products by Clearview AI, a face recognition company.

CONTRACTS AND AGREEMENTS
Any and all agreements related to the acquisition and use of this "software," algorithm, or program. This includes (but is not limited to):
• all contracts (as well as associated amendments, attachments, and exhibits)
• data sharing agreements
• insurance agreements
• intergovernmental services agreements
• licensing agreements
• memorandums of understanding, and
• nondisclosure agreements
• any relevant Requests for Expressions of Interest, Requests For Proposal (or equivalent calls for bids), responses to Requests for Expressions of Interest, letters of interest, responses to Requests for Proposal, sole source or limited source justification and approval documentation, documentation of selection, and other materials generated in the consideration and selection of the technology in question.

FINANCIAL and FUNDING MATERIALS
• Any records related to the financing or funding of this face recognition technology or system, including a copy of any related funding opportunity announcements, grant applications, grantor status/progress reports, purchase orders, invoices, and other memoranda and documentation related to the payment or cost (or lack thereof) of the face recognition technology or system, related technology, personnel, equipment, or other elements concerning this face recognition technology or system or program.

POLICIES, INSTRUCTIONAL, TRAINING, AND USE MATERIALS
• All instructional materials, presentations, and presentation materials (including recorded video and audio, PowerPoint files, prepared remarks, and slides formats), and other guidance on the use of face recognition technology or system. This includes any notes taken during meetings that discussed the use of the software, any explanations (whether generated internally or externally) of how the face recognition technology or system works, and any other document that has been used to help explain the use of the face recognition technology or system to any party, including internal documentation, public relations materials, and executive summaries.
• This also includes training materials governing the use, sharing, or access to the face recognition technology or system or any data related to or collected by the face recognition software/technology, including the legal standard that is required before using the technology.
• Please provide a copy of any policies, policy directives, guidance documents, memoranda, training materials, or similar records governing the use and function of this technology for immigration, law enforcement, or any purpose, including all those related to data retention, permissible and impermissible use, and security standards. This would include materials that describe the application, function, and use of the face recognition technology or system, including advertisements, emails, handouts, usage policies, PowerPoint presentations, specification documents, or standard operating procedures.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

John Snelgrove

 RE: Public Information Act Request of September 25, 2023, Reference # P008161-092523 
Dear John Snelgrove, 
The City of Amarillo has received your public information request dated 9/25/2023 for the following: To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records: 

Materials describing this agency's relationship with and use of products by Clearview AI, a face recognition company. 

CONTRACTS AND AGREEMENTS 
Any and all agreements related to the acquisition and use of this "software," algorithm, or program. This includes (but is not limited to): 
• all contracts (as well as associated amendments, attachments, and exhibits) 
• data sharing agreements 
• insurance agreements 
• intergovernmental services agreements 
• licensing agreements 
• memorandums of understanding, and 
• nondisclosure agreements 
• any relevant Requests for Expressions of Interest, Requests For Proposal (or equivalent calls for bids), responses to Requests for Expressions of Interest, letters of interest, responses to Requests for Proposal, sole source or limited source justification and approval documentation, documentation of selection, and other materials generated in the consideration and selection of the technology in question. 

FINANCIAL and FUNDING MATERIALS 
• Any records related to the financing or funding of this face recognition technology or system, including a copy of any related funding opportunity announcements, grant applications, grantor status/progress reports, purchase orders, invoices, and other memoranda and documentation related to the payment or cost (or lack thereof) of the face recognition technology or system, related technology, personnel, equipment, or other elements concerning this face recognition technology or system or program. 

POLICIES, INSTRUCTIONAL, TRAINING, AND USE MATERIALS 
• All instructional materials, presentations, and presentation materials (including recorded video and audio, PowerPoint files, prepared remarks, and slides formats), and other guidance on the use of face recognition technology or system. This includes any notes taken during meetings that discussed the use of the software, any explanations (whether generated internally or externally) of how the face recognition technology or system works, and any other document that has been used to help explain the use of the face recognition technology or system to any party, including internal documentation, public relations materials, and executive summaries. 
• This also includes training materials governing the use, sharing, or access to the face recognition technology or system or any data related to or collected by the face recognition software/technology, including the legal standard that is required before using the technology. 
• Please provide a copy of any policies, policy directives, guidance documents, memoranda, training materials, or similar records governing the use and function of this technology for immigration, law enforcement, or any purpose, including all those related to data retention, permissible and impermissible use, and security standards. This would include materials that describe the application, function, and use of the face recognition technology or system, including advertisements, emails, handouts, usage policies, PowerPoint presentations, specification documents, or standard operating procedures. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

John Snelgrove

title: FOIA Request - MROs

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA Request - MROs
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act and Privacy Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552. I hereby request the following records:

All documents related to MRO policy or policies, procedures, training manual(s), and AAMRO certification within your agency's possession from 2019 to 2023, on the day this request is processed.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that fees cannot be waived, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

I would also appreciate an approximate time frame for this request to be processed. Depending of the time frame for the request to be fulfilled and any fees that may be incurred, I may revise the criteria.

If you deny any part of this request, please cite each specific exemption you think justifies your refusal to release the information and notify me of appeal procedures available under the law.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Bailey Pillon

title: S1 ERO Taskers for Stewart Detention Center 2021-2022 (Immigration and Customs Enforcement)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: S1 ERO Taskers for Stewart Detention Center 2021-2022 (Immigration and Customs Enforcement)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Background: 
In July 2021, Vice News released a video showing former DHS Secretary Janet Napolitano calling on Secretary Mayorkas to close the Stewart Detention Center, operated for ICE by CoreCivic in Lumpkin, Georgia. Secretary Mayorkas appeared in the video as well. In this videotaped interview, the Secretary stated that DHS is looking into facilities across the nation, and that "Stewart is one" of these facilities. Secretary Mayorkas committed to taking action if DHS's investigation into Stewart revealed inhumane treatment. 

In July 2022, four women formerly detained at Stewart filed a complaint alleging sexual abuse and harassment by a male medical provider at Stewart, and retaliation and unlawful PREA violations in the subsequent investigation ICE allowed CoreCivic to conduct into these allegations. 

Description of Records Sought:
Please provide (1) any Taskers regarding the Stewart Detention Center between January 20, 2021 and the present, from the Secretary of Homeland Security's Office to ICE or DHS HQ or any other DHS agency component, and (2) the responses received by the Office of the Secretary to each Tasker. 

Thank you, 

Andrew Free
#DetentionKills Transparency Initiative
Al Otro Lado

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

communications.subject: ICE FOIA Case Number 2023-ICFO-03850
communications.communication:
12/21/2022Andrew FreeMuckRock News, DEPT MR136690Boston, Massachusetts 02115 RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2023-ICFO-03850        Dear Requester:This acknowledges receipt of your 11/13/2022, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for records pertaining to  July 2021, Vice News released a video showing former DHS Secretary Janet Napolitano calling on Secretary Mayorkas to close the Stewart Detention Center, operated for ICE by CoreCivic in Lumpkin, Georgia. Secretary Mayorkas appeared in the video as well. In this videotaped interview, the Secretary stated that DHS is looking into facilities across the nation, and that "Stewart is one" of these facilities. Secretary Mayorkas committed to taking action if DHS's investigation into Stewart revealed inhumane treatment. In July 2022, four women formerly detained at Stewart filed a complaint alleging sexual abuse and harassment by a male medical provider at Stewart, and retaliation and unlawful PREA violations in the subsequent investigation ICE allowed CoreCivic to conduct into these allegations. Description of Records Sought: Please provide (1) any Taskers regarding the Stewart Detention Center between January 20, 2021 and the present, from the Secretary of Homeland Security's Office to ICE or DHS HQ or any other DHS agency component, and (2) the responses received by the Office of the Secretary to each Tasker. Thank you, Andrew Free #DetentionKills Transparency Initiative Al Otro Lado.  Your request was received in this office on 11/13/2022.Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner.Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to non-commercial requesters.  As a non-commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free, as are the first two hours of search time, after which you will pay the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued.We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request.If you have any questions, please contact FOIA Public Liaison, Marcus Francis at the address above or (866) 633-1182. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769.Your request has been assigned reference number 2023-ICFO-03850. communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: McLennan County Administrator Dustin Chapman Exit Interviews
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Exit interviews from December 2022 until the present from all jailers deputies, and civilians, all employees until the present.
Employment history, date of employment, raises, schools, etc. of Katy Taylor, including all raises and current position and rate of pay.
Employment history of Jacob Atkinson, including pay.
Date of move by Richard Conoley from the Hwy 84 jail to the Jack Harwell.  Employment file of Richard Conoley including reprimands, letters to HR, and complaints, starting pay, starting location, present location, and pay.
Exit interview of Pam Whitlock.
All sexual harassment complaints against Richard Conoley from his start date to the present.
Employment history, and jailer license of Brandy Burson, including starting pay to the present, all schools, promotions.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Bernadette Feazell

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #FOIL-2023-017-00081
communications.communication:
In my prior dealings with city agency FOIL requests, I have seen the city proffer dates 60 days ahead as the expected completion date, only to further delay by 60 days on that date. More than one agency illegally repeated this at least a half dozen times.

Can I expect this FOIL request to actually be completed on or before Tuesday, January 2, 2024? If not, I will not hesitate to appeal on grounds of constructive denial.

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #FOIL-2023-017-00081
communications.communication:
It has been approximately 12 business days since my November 20 communication requesting confirmation that Tuesday, January 2, 2024 is the honest, sincere, intentional, and realistic completion date for this request.

Let the record reflect that I am attempting to work with the agency in good faith, and give them opportunities to comply with the letter and spirit of the law.

Absent further confirmation, I think it's reasonable to assume the agency shall produce responsive documents on or before Tuesday, January 2, 2024, to meet their own schedule. If documents are not produced by then, or if the estimated completion date is extended further, I will not hesitate to appeal on grounds of constructive denial.

communications.subject: [OpenRecords] Request FOIL-2023-017-00081 Closed
communications.communication:
The NYC Office of Emergency Management (OEM) has closed your FOIL request FOIL-2023-017-00081 for the following reasons: (https://a860-openrecords.nyc.gov/request/view/FOIL-2023-017-00081) 
 Your request under the Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) is denied in part and granted in part for the reasons stated below. 
  * Please note that documents have been withheld and/or redactions have been made pursuant to New York Public Officers Law §§87(2)b, d, f, and g. 
You may appeal the decision to deny access to material that was redacted in part or withheld in entirety by contacting the agency's FOIL Appeals Officer: foilrequests@oem.nyc.gov within 30 days. (mailto:foilrequests@oem.nyc.gov?subject=FOIL-2023-017-00081%20-%20Appeal)

title: COMP TIME BALANCES AND PAID COMP TIME 2018 TO CURRENT

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: COMP TIME BALANCES AND PAID COMP TIME 2018 TO CURRENT
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1.      "Comp Time" accrual balances for all  Sheriff's Office personnel both paid and unpaid the amounts and to whom it was paid 
          From 01/01/2018 to 12/15/2023 

2.     I am also, requesting overtime paid from  01/01/2018 to 12/15/2023 for all Sheriff's Office personal amounts and to whom it was paid.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Bernadette Feazell

communications.subject: Re: Texas Public Information Act Request: COMP TIME BALANCES AND PAID COMP TIME 2018 TO CURRENT
communications.communication:
Attached is information showing the comp time/overtime earned and comp time/overtime paid for each payroll in the requested period.
Thank you,
Frances Bartlett

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: P.O.s, Requisition Requests
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Please provide me with P.O.s, requisition requests, or any form used to request the purchase of items  for the McLennan County Jail and The Jack Harwell Detention Center for the following,

January the 1st 2017 until December 31st, 2017
January the 1st 2018 until December 31st, 2018
January the 1st 2019 until December 31st, 2019, to include the takeover of the Jack Harwell Detention Center in September 2019
January the 1st 2020 until December 31st, 2020
January the 1st 2021 until December 31st, 2021
January the 1st 2022 until December 31st, 2022
January the 1st 2023 until November 28th, 2023

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Bernadette Feazell

title: FOIA Request: Agreements

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: FOIA Request: Agreements
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

A copy of all agreements that were active between 1/1/2022 and 12/15/2023 with each of the following institutions:

- Southern Illinois University Edwardsville
- University of Missouri St. Louis

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

e

title: Call Records For NorthCom

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Call Records For NorthCom
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Please furnish the incoming and outgoing call records from the dispatch center on the date of 12.5.2023 for the phone number 561-320-7690, please include the incoming caller ID, who answered the phone, their name and ID number and the recordings of the calls.

There should be no feed associated with this request. I would ask that this request be filled via email per Florida Sunshine Law.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Mason C. Turner

title: Form ACF-202

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Form ACF-202
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

California's Form ACF-202 (TANF Caseload Reduction Report) for fiscal year 2023.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Gabrielle Pepin

title: NASA support for 2009 film "The Box"

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: NASA support for 2009 film "The Box"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any documents pertaining to collaboration between the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) and the production of the 2009 movie "The Box," directed by Richard Kelly and starring Cameron Diaz. I request any and all documents pertaining to NASA support for "The Box." Such documents may include but should not be limited to: script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of NASA and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "The Box," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: NARA PF 12.13.23
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

You are receiving this correspondence as a request under the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. subsection 552. I am requesting access to the following records in the possession of the National Archives and Record Administration (NARA):

All records related to Project Fantasia. Project Fantasia was a collaboration between the Office of Strategic Services (record group 226) and the Office of Scientific Research and Development (record group 227), and was assigned a project number of SAC-26. A 2016 article published by NARA in Prologue Magazine, titled "Secret Weapons, Forgotten Sacrifices," contains a description of Project Fantasia and identifies some of the records as being in record group 227. It can be found here: https://www.archives.gov/publications/prologue/2016/spring/office-scientific-research-development-world-war-ii

Please restrict your search for any records to record groups 226 and 227.

I would prefer to review these records in-person, at your location in College Park, Maryland. If any of these records are being held at a facility other than the one in College Park, please notify me of this before processing the request.

I look forward to your response within 20 working days, as the statute requires. If access to the records I am requesting will take longer, please advise which tier of processing queue this request falls under and an estimated time frame for processing.

If you deny any or all of this request, please cite each specific exemption you feel justifies the refusal to release the information and notify me of the appeal procedures available to me under the law.

If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said destruction or transfer, to include but not be limited to confirmation that NARA has no other copies of said records.

Sincerely,

Robert Skvarla, Jr.

communications.subject: [24-13703]- Freedom of Information Act Request- Robert Skvarla, Jr.
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Skvarla:

This is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request of December
13, 2023, regarding Record Group 226 *Records of the Office of Strategic
Services (OSS) *and Record Group 227 *Records of the Office of Scientific
Research and Development [OSRD]* records pertaining to Project Fantasia
(SAC-26), which was a joint OSS/OSRD project to create a luminescent
balloon as a psychological weapon against the Japanese during World War II.

Your request was received by my office on December 19, 2023 and assigned
tracking number 24-13703.

Using the search terms "Fantasia" and "SAC-26" to guide us, we have
carefully searched the Topical Index and the Code Name Index
for Record Group 226 *Records of the Office of Strategic Services (OSS), *which
references documents held throughout the record group. We also searched the
file list for Record Group 226 Entry A1 145 *Records of the Office of
Strategic Services. Research and Development Branch. Subject Files,
1942–1945*, which developed or contracted for the fabrication of special
weapons and devices. However, we were not able to locate any records
responsive to your FOIA request.

We were able to locate one Project Fantasia (SAC-26)-related file, which is
open to the public and contains approximately 60 pages, in Record Group 227
Entry NC 118 151 *Records of the Office of Scientific Research and
Development. Project or Problem Files, 1942–1946*, Box 74 [STACK LOCATION:
130/22/12/4]. We would be happy to help you access these records in
the Civilian Records Consultation Area of the National Archives at College
Park, MD <https://www.archives.gov/college-park> (Archives II) Textual
Research Room (3rd Floor). You may request an appointment
<https://www.eventbrite.com/cc/textual-research-room-appointments-487599> to
do so online.

As an alternative to visiting Archives II, you may wish to hire a private
researcher to access the records on your behalf.  A list of private
researchers who are familiar with Archives II is available on our website
<https://www.archives.gov/research/hire-help/locations.html?facility=college-park>
.

We do not consider this a denial of your FOIA request. However, if you are
not satisfied with our action, your options for appeal and dispute
resolution are outlined in the attachment.

This completes the processing of your FOIA request.

Sincerely,

ERIC van SLANDER

Textual Reference Archives II Branch (RR2RR)
National Archives at College Park, MD

title: Data Breach Union County FL

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Untitled
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, we hereby request the following information:

Your agency name
Your agency state
Your agency type   Business, Education K12, Education Higher
Your agency CEO

Breach is defined for this request as
A: An external actor that forcibly entered the system and accessed information
B: An internal actor that released or shared information that was not appropriate to share or shared intentionally without regard for entity protocol.

Please list any breach that was reported using the following format for the time period July 1, 2021 until July 1, 2023. Label each breach logically as Breach 1 or Breach 2, etc.*List each breach categorized as a document or an email as a separate breach.

For each breach provide the following information
1. Was this event for documents or email?
2. Date breach was reported
3. The position of the person reporting the breach
4. Highest position of  administration the breach was reported to for the agency
5. Was the process or procedure for evaluating and notifying those impacted followed? 
6. Were stakeholders with breached data notified?   If so, what timeline after the breach was reported (weeks, days, hours)  to the CEO listed above was the notification sent to those impacted?
7. What method(s) was used to notify stakeholders of the breach? Example, newspaper, social media, email, phone, mail, etc.
8. Was any protection such as credit monitoring or other protective opportunities provided to stakeholders affected?
9. Was the breached information considered protected under HIPAA or FERPA?
10. Count of records breached for category 1 above. (Emails and documents should NOT be included in the same count but reported as separate events even if the same date)
11. If the agency's process or procedure for evaluating and notification were not followed, what was the reasoning and by whom was the decision made to not follow the process or procedure?

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,
FOIA Disclosure Group

Breach 1 - MIS Director
Breach 2 - MIS Director

4. Highest position of administration the breach was reported to for the agency
Breach 1 - Superintendent
Breach 2 - Superintendent

5. Was the process or procedure for evaluating and notifying those impacted followed? 
Breach 1 - MIS Director notified two of the Critical Incident Response team members, however the complete team was not convened because the nature of the documents were not deemed a breach as defined by the District’s IRP.
Breach 2 - MIS Director notified two of the Critical Incident Response team members, however the complete team was not convened because the nature of the emails were not deemed a breach as defined by the District’s IRP.

6. Were stakeholders with breached data notified?   If so, what timeline after the breach was reported (weeks, days, hours)  to the CEO listed above was the notification sent to those impacted?
Breach 1 - No, upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 
Breach 2 - No, upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 

7. What method(s) was used to notify stakeholders of the breach? Example, newspaper, social media, email, phone, mail, etc.
Breach 1 - None, due to the understanding of the requirements listed in the Incident Response Plan
Breach 2 - None, due to the understanding of the requirements listed in the Incident Response Plan

8. Was any protection such as credit monitoring or other protective opportunities provided to stakeholders affected?
Breach 1 - The incident did not result in the release of personal information as defined in the District’s IRP 
Breach 2 - The incident did not result in the release of personal information as defined in the District’s IRP 

9. Was the breached information considered protected under HIPAA or FERPA?
Breach 1 - FERPA
Breach 2 - FERPA

10. Count of records breached for category 1 above. (Emails and documents should NOT be included in the same count but reported as separate events even if the same date)
Breach 1 - 1246
Breach 2 - 1067 - This total indicates the number of times the email in question had any type of activity, not necessarily resulting in any type of breach. 

11. If the agency's process or procedure for evaluating and notification were not followed, what was the reasoning and by whom was the decision made to not follow the process or procedure?
Breach 1 - Upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 
Breach 2 - Upon review of the documents and the District’s Incident Response Plan (IRP), these documents were not deemed “critical” by the Superintendent. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.
Sincerely,
FOIA Disclosure Group

Initially your response was the CEO unilaterally determined (outside the scope of the entity's process) the events were not critical and the sharing and viewing of protected information was not a breach (Hillsborough Schools just reported an event as a breach where only 250 records were improperly viewed, far less than your entity).

3. Also, this is by no means  saying the information is not correct but just wanted to confirm for the official record responded to on August 22, 2023.  As of the date of the second breach reporting, October 31, 2022, the official statement is no other emails or document sharing occurred between the individuals that created the breach after this reporting date.  This is not saying the information is not correct but it seems rare that the email and communications between the individuals involved in the breach ceased on the same day the breach was reported. title: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act request concerning Patric Patterson

communications.subject: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act request concerning Patric Patterson
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arkansas Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All publicly releasable records held by your agency concerning the incident that occurred on or around March 16, 2014 at the Varner Unit involving inmate Patric Patterson (ADC #107498) and inmate Michael Black, in which Black allegedly assaulted Patterson, including but not limited to:

— Incident report(s), including investigative notes and narrative descriptions
— Chronological record of events
— Property log(s)
— Memorandums, memos, and notes referencing the incident
— All photos, audio, and surveillance video of or concerning the incident, including but not limited to stationary pod footage, handheld camera footage, and other surveillance materials
— ADC policy prohibiting officers from entering the barracks alone

If you determine that any of the information qualifies for an exemption from disclosure, I ask you to note whether the exemption is discretionary, and if so whether it is necessary in this case to exercise your discretion to withhold the information. In any event, please provide a signed notification citing the legal authorities on which you rely if you determine that any of the information is exempt and will not be disclosed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sonny Albarado, a citizen of Arkansas, in coordination with Nicole Einbinder.

communications.subject: Re: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act request concerning Patric Patterson

communications.subject: FW: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act request concerning Patric Patterson
communications.communication:
Sonny Albarado,

The Arkansas Department of Corrections received your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request regarding the incident that occurred on March 16, 2014.  According to Ark. Code Ann § 25-19-105(a)(1)(A), FOIA requests can only be made by citizens of the State of Arkansas.  Although you state that you are a citizen of the state of Arkansas in your request, the address that you provided was for MuckRock News and it is not an Arkansas address.  In order for us to proceed, please provide us with a mailing address as proof that you are a citizen of the state of Arkansas.


Thank you,
LATISHA MEADOWS
Quality Assurance Coordinator
Arkansas Department of Corrections
Phone: 1-501-537-7677
Email: Latisha.Meadows@arkansas.gov<mailto:Latisha.Meadows@arkansas.gov>

communications.subject: RE: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act request concerning Patric Patterson
communications.communication:
Sonny Albarado,

"On December 4, 2023, the Arkansas Department of Corrections received your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request regarding the incident that occurred on March 16, 2014.  It is uncertain whether you are a citizen of the state of Arkansas; as a result, on December 5, 2023, I sent you an email requesting that you verify whether you are a citizen of the State of Arkansas.  I did not receive a response.  According to Ark. Code Ann. § 25-19-105(a)(1)(A), a request under Arkansas FOIA can only be made by a citizen of the state of Arkansas.  We have no proof that you are a citizen of the state of Arkansas; as a result, we cannot release any requested information and your request is denied.

 

 

Thank you,

LATISHA MEADOWS

Quality Assurance Coordinator

Arkansas Department of Corrections

Phone: 1-501-537-7677

Email: Latisha.Meadows@arkansas.gov"

communications.subject: FOIA Response for SBA-2019-000560
communications.communication:
Good morning,

We are in receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request that you submitted to the U.S. Small Business Administration (SBA) on May 13, 2019, and received in our office on May 13, 2019. We have assigned your request tracking number SBA-2019-000560, please use this tracking number when referring to your request in the future.

Please be aware that the FOIA provides a right of access to federal agency records that exist and can be located in agency files. The FOIA does not require agencies to answer questions in response to FOIA requests. However, we will make an exception and process your request.

Item 1: we can provide the number of site visits since 2011 (see attached).
Item 2: no records.
Item 3: this portion of the request has been referred to the Office of the Chief Financial Officer for response.

If you are not satisfied with this action, you may appeal this decision to the Chief, Freedom of Information/Privacy Acts Office, U.S. Small Business Administration, 409 Third St., SW, Washington, DC 20416. You must submit an appeal within 90 calendar days of the date of the notice of denial. Your appeal should contain a copy of this correspondence, a description of the information requested in addition to what was denied, the name and title of the SBA official or employee who denied the request, the reason for the denial, and any other facts you deem appropriate.

The 2007 FOIA amendments created the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) to offer mediation services to resolve disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation. Using OGIS services does not affect your right to pursue litigation. You may contact OGIS in any of the following ways:

Office of Government Information Services
National Archives and Records Administration
8601 Adelphi Road - OGIS
College Park, MD 20740-6001
E-mail: ogis@nara.gov<mailto:ogis@nara.gov>
Telephone: 202-741-5770
Toll-free: 1-877-684-6448

Please note that using OGIS services does not affect the timing of filing an appeal with the SBA's FOI/PA Officer.

Thank you for your interest in the Small Business Administration.


v/r

Davida Bobo
Administrative Officer, Operations
Government Contracting and Business Development
U.S. Small Business Administration

davida.bobo@sba.gov<mailto:davida.bobo@sba.gov>

[SBA-Hor-2]

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

communications.subject: City of Seattle Public Records Request Center - Invoice Ready :: C155526-100923
communications.communication:
Dear Rose Terse, 
 
Records in response to your public disclosure request C155526-100923 received on October 09, 2023 are now available. The cost for the records is as follows: 
 
Invoice Number: INV23-C155526-1 
Total: $1.25 
 
To pay online, please follow these steps: 
 Please note that you will need to disable any pop-up blockers to make a payment using the system. 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Find this request: C155526-100923. 
  * Select the 'View Invoices' button. 
 
  * Opens a pop-up window showing your invoice: INV23-C155526-1. 
  * Click on the invoice and then the 'Pay Now' button. 
  * Continue processing your payment. 
  * Select 'Done'. 
  * Once the payment process is done, you are returned to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * After your payment is successful you will receive an email from our payments center. 
Once your payment has been approved, we will send you an email with instructions on how to download your records. Note that City staff must manually upload records. Records will be available one to two business days after payment. 
 
Please let your public disclosure officer (PDO) know if you are unable to pay online; your PDO will work with you on alternative ways to make your payment. 
 
You have 30 days from today's date to pay for your records. If the City does not receive your payment within this time period, your request will be considered abandoned, and you will need to submit a new request. 
 Please add seattle@mycusthelp.net to your E-mail contacts/address book to ensure delivery of the record center E-mails to your Inbox. (mailto:seattle@mycusthelp.net) 
This is an auto-generated email and has originated from an unmonitored email account. Please DO NOT REPLY.

title: Diego Maradona (Federal Bureau of Investigation)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Diego Maradona (Federal Bureau of Investigation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documents about or concerning Diego Maradona (October 30, 1960 – November 25, 2020). Proof of death is not required since his death this month was widely reported.

Please search the Central Index, cross-reference and ELSUR documents.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alfred Spellman

communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 104 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 853 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,786 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,500 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: FOIA request (case 21-00021-FR)
communications.communication:
Dear Alfred Spellman,

Pursuant to you recent FOIA request (case 21-00021-FR), I will be forwarding our final determination response via email. We have determined that some of the records contain sensitive information that requires encryption as explained below.

In an effort to better protect information that the Department of Justice (DOJ) maintains about individuals, we have implemented a tool to prevent accidental disclosures of sensitive personally identifiable information (PII). Documents that are responsive to a FOIA or Privacy Act request may contain sensitive PII. To safeguard this information, any email containing sensitive PII will be encrypted. Accordingly, you may receive an alert that that an encrypted message has been delivered to you. Should you receive such an alert, please use the attached instruction to decrypt and save the message. If you have any issues with this process, please reply with the error message received so that we may contact our service desk for support.

V/R
Jason T. Miller
FOIA Analyst II
Freedom of Information and Privacy Act Unit
FOIA and Information Law Section
Drug Enforcement Administration
Desk: (571) 776-3436
Email: Jason.T.Miller2@dea.gov<mailto:Jason.T.Miller2@dea.gov>

[https://intranet13.shpt.sbu.dea.doj.gov/sites/cp/PublishingImages/Pages/DEA-50th-Anniversary-News/50th%20Anniversary%20Email%20Signature%20Block_329x83.png]

PRIVACY ACT NOTICE:  This e-mail (including any attachments herein) may contain personal and privileged information that requires protection in compliance with the Privacy Act of 1974 (5 U.S.C. § 552a).  Any use of this information by anyone other than the intended recipient is prohibited.  If you have received this communication in error, please immediately delete all copies of this information and notify me by e-mail.  The use, dissemination, distribution, or reproduction of this communication by unintended recipients is not authorized and may be unlawful
